	<h2 style="text-align:center">Ruby on Rails</h2>
	<h3>MVC Architecture</h3>
	<p>Rails is made of a Model-View-Control architecture:<br><br>Model is your database<br><br>View is your web page<br><br>Control is the backend code of your web application</p>
	<h3>Creating your first page</h3>
	<p>If you go to the <i>Ruby</i> directory you made on the previous page, you'll find a variety of sub-directories. The one we'll be focusing on is the <i>app</i> directory.</p>
	<p>Creating a web page involes initializing a controller and a view, you can do so by running the following command:<br><br>
		<code>
				cd Ruby
		</code><br><br>
		This puts you into the directory you made on the previous page, next run:<br><br>
		<code>
				rails generate controller home index 
		</code><br><br>
	</p>
	<h3>View</h3>
	<p>
		The command above created a new view in the <i>views</i> sub-directory of <i>apps</i>. You can access the view in the <i>app/views/home/index.html.erb</i> file.<br><br>
		From now on, you can create your webpage in regular html from <i>index.html.erb</i> . You can access it via url using <i>http://localhost:3000/home/index</i>
	</p>
	<h3>Demonstration</h3>
	<p>Let's make an example webpage with Semantic UI and Ruby on Rails <br><br>
	In your <i>index.html.erb</i> file, let's create a <a href="https://fomantic-ui.com/collections/grid.html" target="_blank">grid</a> that shows <a href="https://fomantic-ui.com/views/card.html" target="_blank">cards</a> of different animals. With Semantic UI, you can organize elements
	into rows and columns of a specified size. For this example, let's make a grid of 4 columns with centered elements: <br><br>
	<code>&lt;div class="ui four column center aligned grid"&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class="row"&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;<br>&lt;/div&gt;</code><br><br>
	For each row, we can include 4 elements of class column. In each column we can put an element of Semantic UI class card. The card class 
	allows you to put images and text in their own good-looking "card" with an image section, and a content section for the title and description. <br><br>
	
	<code>
		&lt;div class="ui card"&gt;<br>
			&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class="image"&gt;<br>
				&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/10/26/science/21tb-tuskless/21tb-tuskless-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg"&gt;<br>
			&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;<br>
			&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class="content"&gt;<br>
				&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;a class="header"&gt;African Elephant&lt;/a&gt;<br>
				&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class="description"&gt;<br>
					&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The African Elephant is the largest land mammal in Africa.<br>
				&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;<br>
			&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;<br>
		&lt;/div&gt;<br>
	</code>
	
	<br><br>For example, here is how the card of an Elephant would look: <br><br>
	
